comments: If you’re keeping in pots, you’ll need to repot in much bigger container. Don’t raise soil level higher than it is currently. Set a schedule to fertilize about every 6 weeks with citrus fertilizer. Water about once a week. I’ve had a Meyer Lemon and a lime (don’t remember variety) for 7 years in pots. I usually bring inside for winter (8b zone). But this year I’ve covered with plastic against my house in sunniest spot. We’ve had several hard freezes so I’m not sure how it will work out. My inside spot is just too small now, plus I fight with scale every winter. The trees are much happier outside. I may change back next year if I have bad luck outside!

caption: 🍊 Citrus trees at Costco! I love them!! 🍋
comments:
To water the trees, purchase half gallon drippers. Young trees from ages 1-2 years will do okay with 4-6 hours of water during spring and 6-10 hours of water in the Summer PER WEEK. 

As they grow older in years 3 and on, convert to Bowsmith Orange A Fan jet emitters. These will release more water. In this growth stage, 12 hours in the spring and 18-24 hours in the summer every week is recommended. 

Overwatering can cause phytophthora, a common soil borne disease. When tested, most roots are found with some of phytophthora, but it can get out of hand if improperly managed. 

Fertilize with 10-10-10 and/or 15-15-15.

A combination of Calcium Nitrate and manure can be a good method for fertilization as well. It’s important to monitor salts through this process and to have proper timing with applications. 

Watch for common target pests like mites, thrips, citrus scale. Use the appropriate methods like systemic pesticides to treat the tree. 

Based on the type of tree, pruning and suckering is also essential for new growth and overall tree health.

📝 Buffalo Chicken Dip Recipe

Ingredients

✔️ 2 cups cooked, shredded chicken (rotisserie chicken is what I used)
✔️ 8 oz cream cheese, softened
✔️ 1/2 cup Frank’s RedHot sauce 
✔️ 1/2 cup ranch 
✔️ 1 cup shredded cheddar cheese (plus extra for topping)
Sliced chives for garnish

Instructions

Preheat Oven: Preheat your oven to 375°F.

In a large bowl, combine the chicken, cream cheese, Frank’s RedHot sauce, cheese and ranch dressing. Stir until smooth.

Spread the mixture into a cast iron skillet or 8x8-inch baking dish. Sprinkle additional cheddar cheese on top.

Bake: Bake for 20-25 minutes, or until the dip is hot and bubbly.

Garnish and Serve: Remove from the oven, garnish with chives (optional), and serve warm.

Serving Suggestions:

Serve with tortilla chips, celery sticks, carrots, or crackers for dipping!

Other things to keep in mind is that it needs well draining soil, so adding a good amount of perlite to the soil will help with this. Finally, a secret ingredient I use for all prunus plants is to water them with rice water that has seaweed extract in it. It makes them grow fast and is high in nutrients. They also need A LOT of sunlight. The more the better.

comments: Oh wow! Love to see it. I know people always hate on pet strollers but there are so many benefits: socializing an unvaccinated puppy to the outside world during their critical learning periods without exposing them to diseases on the ground before their shots,  a way for elderly dogs to have environmental enrichment and sniff things when they can’t walk well anymore, dogs with anxiety who need acclimitization to surroundings safely without being a flight risk, a way for smaller dogs to take a break from walking but still be included with everyone, allowing cats who hate harnesses/leashes to enjoy the outside safely, socializing a service dog puppy to new non-pet friendly environments and sounds without being a disruption to others, safely traveling and walking with disabled or “wobbly” pets (neuro disorders)  etc.

caption: Backyard upgrade! ☀️ I would add the string lights from Costco! And maybe the shades too!
comments: We have this in white on our back patio and it transformed the space. We really enjoy it. Live in the Chicagoland area so it’s been through all seasons without rusting or major issues for about two years so far. We did not treat or do anything special. We did not originally anchor it since it’s so heavy, but have dealt with some nasty storm winds that did end up shuffling this thing in the middle of the night even when the slats are open. Scary. It’s now anchored using new anchors from the store since the ones provided are 🗑️. When the slats are closed the coverage is fully dry underneath when raining, which surprised me. Setup wasn’t too bad as I did most of the prep myself but needed at least one other person to get the pillars connected. I have no major complaints so far.

comments: I say that this louvered pergola is the greatest purchase I ever made. Going on 3 yrs. It’s on concrete bolted on 2 of 3 legs. I bought one screen to put on the west side to block afternoon sun and the neighbor. I forgot to open the louvers this winter and had no issues with 5” of snow. The mechanism has not rusted. We sit under it in rainstorms and only get wet if it’s a sideways rain. The gutter works well and the items below are dry. It took two men 12 hrs to assemble it. Also, I have 3 cats and none of them have shown interest, but if they did it would perfectly hide the snags. Yes it is firm but I like having support and not falling into a couch that’s hard to get out of. What I love about this couch is that it is perfect for two people without a big footprint in our living room. The curved sides are great for smaller spaces. And life is short- get the white furniture if you want to and leave your dirty shoes at the door. 😬

comments:
I work with fragrance, let me tell you something:
I just wanted to jump in on the candles and fragrance talk. So, yeah, some candles can be toxic—especially the ones made from paraffin wax since they might release harmful stuff when you burn them.
As someone who makes perfume, I can tell you that fragrances really depend on the ingredients. Those with parabens and phthalates can be sketchy, but not every fragrance is bad. When you have fragrances made just from essential oils, they might still cause allergies for some people because a lot of natural ingredients can be triggers.
Bottom line: just because something's 'natural’ doesn’t mean it’s automatically safe, and 'synthetic' doesn’t mean it’s a no-go either. It’s all about being smart and picking what works for you. Let’s spread awareness, not fear!

comments: I took advantage of a similar deal a couple of years ago, where I got sactional, citysac, squattoman, 2 foot sacs, sactional table, two cup holders, and pillows. Cheap? No. But a great value compared to lovesac’s retail store. What I will tell you is, I upgraded to the lovesoft fill and I absolutely regret doing it. It sags, the seats aren’t perfectly rectangular in the covers, and it’s just overall not comfortable at all. I thought it would be one of those things that would take some getting use… but 3 years later, nope. Totally wish I would have just done standard foam. I will also tell you that reconfiguring it is not as easy as it looks and won’t take you 5-10 min if you do it yourself. It’s best if you have someone help you. Otherwise you’re going to need to set sometime to plot how you want it and take your time making sure the legs are secure in the base. Would I buy again? The sactional, no. The citysac and the footsac? Absolutely. Those are fantastic.

comments: I have one similar to this.  The problem is if you have a dog with a double coat and are used to using a brush like a furminator, this whole setup actually ends up making the process longer.. because of the brush on these, even with suction, you have to brush so many times over and over to get even remotely close to the hair that the furminator picks up, it ends up being kinda useless.  The low volume vaccum is nice, but again, if you have a dog that sheds a lot (I have a mix with chow in her), these really don’t work that well.
